%I A395533 #11 May 03 2026 20:01:33
%S A395533 4,1,48,322,1517,3476,45998,405818,591216,43220379,172187609
%N A395533 a(n) is the first occurrence k of an uninterrupted sequence of n adjacent center parts of the symmetric representation of sigma of i, SRS(i), i = k to i = k + n - 1 where each SRS(i) has an odd number of parts and SRS(k-1) and SRS(k+n) each have an even number of parts.
%C A395533 a(n) > 10^7 for all n > 9.
%C A395533 Conjecture: a(n) is increasing for n > 1.
%C A395533 By definition, for any a(n) = k adjacent center parts of SRS(i) and SRS(i+1), k <= i < k+n-1, share a common boundary of at least length 2 about the diagonal.
%C A395533 a(n) is the index of the first occurrence of exactly n consecutive odd numbers in A237271. - _Sean A. Irvine_, May 03 2026
%e A395533 The drawing shows a(1) = 4 and a(2) = 1. Though SRS(4) and SRS(6) share a common boundary of length 2 about the diagonal, SRS(3) and SRS(5) around SRS(4) consist of 2 parts each. The only adjacent neighbor of SRS(1) is SRS(2) and they share a boundary of minimum length 2.
%e A395533   ._ _ _ _
%e A395533  6|_ _ _  |_
%e A395533   ._ _ _|   |_
%e A395533  4|_ _  |_ _  |
%e A395533   ._ _|_  | | |
%e A395533  2|_  | | | | |
%e A395533  1|_|_|.|_|.|_|.
%e A395533    1 2   4   6
%e A395533 a(3) = 48 since SRS(48), SRS(49) and SRS(50) have 1, 3 and 3 parts respectively while SRS(47) and SRS(51) have 2 and 4 parts respectively.
%t A395533 (* function partsSRS[ ] is defined in A320511 *)
%t A395533 oddParts[b_] := Select[Map[{#, Length[partsSRS[#]]}&, Range[b], OddQ[#[[2]]]&]
%t A395533 adjacent[b_] := Split[oddParts[b], #1[[1]]+1==#2[[1]]&]
%t A395533 a395533[b_, c_] := Module[{oPL=adjacent[b], len, list=Table[0, c], i, v}, len=Length[oPL]; For[i=1, i<=len, i++, v=Length[oPL[[i]]]; If[v<=c&&list[[v]]==0, list[[v]]=oPL[[i]][[1, 1]]]]; list]
%t A395533 a395533[2000000, 9] (* long computation time for a(n), n > 7 *)
%Y A395533 Cf. A237593, A240542, A249223, A320511, A237271.
%K A395533 nonn,more,new
